Oct 9 2005	Always Stay at Becks	I've stayed at dozens of different hotels in the Bay Area (including all the very expensive 5 stars), but usually stay at the Becks. Why ? you ask after reading some of the reviews. To tackle the good points, the location is brilliant particularly if you want to be near to the Castro area. Everything is outside the door literally. There are dozens of good cafes for breakfast, and even more for lunch / dinner and lots of coffee shops. A lot of these are filled with locals having a slow breakfast reading the paper, and are quite willing to chat. There's a coffee shop / internet cafe directly opposite along with a good bookstore, Tower Records is a few doors up, a large Safeways for groceries down the road, all the bars of Castro surround you, and ground zero of the Castro gay district is an easy 5 minute walk away. As far as transport, there is the Muni underground, plus historic old trams from all over the world that stop outside the hotel and take you in a straight line down Market Street right into the centre of town. What a way to get there ! Here you can do all the touristy things, cable cars, shopping etc, but get away back to a nice area after. The hotel will cost $100 - 130 or so, which is a fraction of those in downtown, but you are so close. Additionally, particularly if you are a gay man, there are plenty of gay tourists staying here that you can hang out with (particularly good if you happen to be passing thru on your own), and of course, some of these can be &quot;more friendly&quot; if you want them to be. Whilst this means that at times, men hang out of the balcony, they are usually very friendly, and lets face it, with the set-up, no-one is going to break into your room with people watching 24/7 (and there is security on at nighttime who challenges outsiders who just walk in). The other big plus is that the hotel has parking. What a god-send. You can zip out for the day and park when u get pack. Most streets around here have cleaning each night between 2am and 6am - which is no good when wanting to park your car to sleep for the night! On the downside, the majority of rooms face the balcony (the definite choice) but only have windows on the front, which means little airflow. The rooms used to smell of gas, but they overcame this by leaving the heating on low all the time. During the height of summer this is just ridiculous as there is no air-con, but at other times of the year (and lets face it, SF is not San Diego when it comes to weather) this doesn't matter at all - particularly in the evenings. The rooms are clean, the carpet can be ratty, but generally are 1 or 2 double beds, cable TV with 80 odd channels, a walk-in wardrobe, and a decent sized bathroom with vanity lights, fan etc. The trams can be a bit of a problem at night at the front if you are a light sleeper, and the wooden construction, means you can hear people walking on the balconies thru small creaks, but this is nothing too major. These small problems aside, I think for a gay man, the location, car parking, companionship of other guests etc. all make it a good choice particularly for the price. I would never recommend this hotel for straight couples or straight businessmen as they might be put off by other guests standing on the balconies (in reality they shouldn't as they pose no harm and in fact are a security feature), however it is not unknown for non-residents to enter and peer in windows with curtains open in the off chance they are invited in for ---. Just ignore them and they move on straight away - this is the Castro after all, and theres a lot more fish in the sea. Would I take my parents here - probably not but possibly due to the location, ease of access and parking. Would I go alone, bring my partner here, or stay here with mates - definitely. Lesbian couples seem to have a good time as well. Open minded straight couples - yes, but the bible-belt non-worldly types might be offended (or be so oblivious to it all, they might miss everything!). I can't see the point of staying here on business, unless you want the Castro for R&amp;R. When I stayed at Becks last week, I met a gay guy with his straight sister who were both enjoying it tremendously - so it really depends on your mindset of whether you want to be in this location with many gay guests or not.	
